run a torch-tensorrt docker image --->>  sudo docker run --gpus=all --rm -it -v $PWD:/Torch-TensorRT --net=host --ipc=host --ulimit memlock=-1 --ulimit stack=67108864 torch_tensorrt:latest bash
docker jupyter notebook torch-tensorrt ---->>   jupyter notebook --allow-root --ip 0.0.0.0 --port 8888

run docker nvidia pytorch container ------>> sudo docker run --gpus all -it --rm nvcr.io/nvidia/pytorch:xx.xx-py3

run a docker container with a binded network---->>> sudo docker run --gpus all -it --rm -p 8888:8888 nvcr.io/nvidia/pytorch:23.02-py3 //the bind allows you to access ports such as jupyter notebook port
run a docker container with a volume allocated--->>> sudo docker run --gpus all --ipc=host --ulimit memlock=-1 --ulimit stack=67108864 -it -v $(pwd)/project_name:/workspace/project_name --rm nvcr.io/nvidia/pytorch:23.02-py3
if you want to run a file directly e.g, train.py, run ---->>> sudo docker run --gpus all --ipc=host --ulimit memlock=-1 --ulimit stack=67108864 -it -v $(pwd)/project_name:/workspace/project_name --rm nvcr.io/nvidia/pytorch:23.02-py3 python ./project_name/train.py

